The dimension of the range space is taken as the number of singular
values of @var{A} greater than @var{tol}.  If the argument @var{tol} is
missing, it is computed as

@example
max (size (@var{A})) * max (svd (@var{A})) * eps
@end example
@seealso{@ref{doc-null,,null}}
@end deftypefn


@c mgorth src/DLD-FUNCTIONS/mgorth.cc
@anchor{doc-mgorth}
@deftypefn {Loadable Function} {[@var{y}, @var{h}] =} mgorth (@var{x}, @var{v})
Orthogonalize a given column vector @var{x} with respect to a given
orthonormal basis @var{v} using a modified Gram-Schmidt orthogonalization.  
On exit, @var{y} is a unit vector such that:

@example
@group
  norm (@var{y}) = 1
  @var{v}' * @var{y} = 0
  @var{x} = @var{h}*[@var{v}, @var{y}]
@end group
@end example

